\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\f7\lang2057\i\f9\fs24\i\f7\lang1025\i\qj\tx540 20.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s18\qj\tx540{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls1\li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af7\afs24\lang1025\ai\ltrch\dbch\af9\langfe255\hich\f7\fs24\lang2057\i\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057\i{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057\i\b0{ In October 1999, SAA, according to the evidence of Viljoen, adopted a more aggressive approach to the override scheme. In Viljoen\'92s words, he was not prepared to reward agents for generic growth i.e. growth that came about from inflation, as opposed to an 
increase in sales. SAA remedied this by firstly reducing the basic commission from 9% to 7%. Then it made the attainment of override and incremental commission more challenging, either by raising targets annually over and above the rate of inflation, and/o
r raising the point at which incremental commission became payable. At the same time, it increased the rate of the incremental and override commission.}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057\i\b0{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s15{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs45\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f7\fs20\lang2057\i0\b0 Transcript page 577-8.}}}
